      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You can modify the query to use parameterized queries, which are safer and more secure. Here's how you can do it:\n\n```python\nimport sqlite3\n\ndef get_user_data(user_id):\n    conn = sqlite3.connect('users.db')\n    cursor = conn.cursor()\n    query = \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?\"\n    cursor.execute(query, (user_id,))\n    return cursor.fetchone()\n```\n\nBy using a parameterized query, you're telling SQLite to treat `user_id` as a parameter, rather than part of the SQL code itself. This prevents any potential SQL injection attacks, and the scanner should no longer flag this as a critical vulnerability.",
